bio: Winter & Summer: A Memory of Nature and Culture

social_posts.post_text: Bear ate some of this one so I may just paint on the remaining half next winter.
Going on ten years with the longbow.
Cutting firewood by hand breathes new meaning in every fire.
Break for lunch on Smith River Complex North. Thank you, Heilung @amplifiedhistory
These last moons have been unreal, wild, rewarding. Here, out from working nights on fire onto the hunt and harvest.

More than a hundred miles later, on a hunt in the high winds I halted. The wind battered from every direction at once, spinning bearing and blinding with ice. Madness bellowed so I would head back, check on a group of deer, and retire from the storm. Giving the area a day to rest, I returned in good weather to pickup hunting the peak rut. I wouldn’t have the wind for getting in but knowledge turned into wisdom. […]

November the ninth, near the new moon. The first wolf up and out, dawn-walking through the bending shadows of a winter wood. When the light would rise and wake the wind, I would turn its course to my advantage. High on the mountain, a mule deer buck, Forki, chased a pod of does as they rummaged for breakfast. I circled the mountain wide to intercept any bruiser hidden in the timber, seeking a mature animal to harvest. These old bones ached, creaked with the joints of my pack. So, with a glad heart, I accepted that the third time Forki offered a shot I would take it.

The season had been a marathon across new ground, further than atvs could drive or many other hunters would trek; through the home of grizzlies, speaking thanks; to the pitch of the elk rut, screaming with bulls, contending for harems; disappearing into the silence, surrounded by wild, cunning animals; hunting dark-to-dark, through rain, sleet, snow, hail, through wind and across waters; valley to summit over many mountains, day after day. It was time to harvest. And on this day, the woods presented a prize, an offering, our endless return. […]

Wide around the deer, along a rub-line and above a scrape contest, I cut elk tracks. I hunkered down around solar noon and heard the thunder of hooves as a bull appeared, southeast at sixty yards. A bushy quartering shot in a moment belonging to instinct. The bull staggered. Hearts pounding, the followup. Blood-trailing, circling each other, and four hours later a raven hinted the direction turning true. This elk was a champion, tough to takedown, fighting to the very last. […]

I stayed through the night to defend my animal, to keep the food to feed my own. In turns tending to a snowy twig fire and field dressing; pausing to look for glowing eyes, have a bite of raw liver or roasted heart. Resting a moment by the fire, on the hide there would not be much time for sleep next to meat, covered in blood. With the first load ready, I set to busting through rough country, down the mountain about the same time that mountain lions hunt. It was a great time! […]

A glad heart sings love and respect, gives thanks for the honor, lives to see the return of the sun.

Our presence is the gift, our balance, the honor. In any language, in any age our thanks rise to the god wind, guiding sense and steps, bringing death and giving life; the god water, flowing through and flowing on; the god earth, standing tall and growing strong; the god fire, bringing light and warmth, the grasp of wild powers. To the crowned bull, Again-Walker, gift of the woods, great king: thank you, forever. [∞]

The next two days would add twenty-eight more mountain-miles to bring the elk home. It’s one of the most challenging-rewarding things that I’ve ever done and such chances sing the love of fate. My thanks pressed into every print and spoken to the taste of fir needles; awe and reverence in each heartbeat given to the cold.
